04509nam a22006975i 9781474469272DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221996stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814744692727 a10.1515/97814744692722doi  a(DE-B1597)616232  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 4aPN3503 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809.3/93582201 aHolton, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJarring Witnesses :bModern Fiction and the Representation of History /cRobert Holton. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPostmodern Theory : POTH00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPart I History and narrative -- t1 Historical narrative and the politics of point of view -- t2 Common sense and historical narrative -- tPart II Modernism and orthodoxy -- t3 Nostromo and the ‘torrent of rubbish’ -- t4 Parade’s End: ‘Has the British this or that come to this!’ -- t5 Absalom, Absalom!: The ‘nigger in the woodpile’ -- tPart III Postmodernism and heterodoxy -- t6 Bearing witness: African-American women’s fiction -- t7 V.: In the rathouse of history with Thomas Pynchon -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJarring Witnesses begins by surveying the problem of point of view as a formal, cognitive and cultural determinant in narrative historiography, particularly in the way certain dominant forms of 'legitimate' history have necessitated the suppresson of the voices of 'jarring witnesses'. The theory is explored in relation to Pierre Bourdieu's theories of doxa and heterodoxy, Bakhtin's concept of heteroglossia, and postmodernism. With this theoretical framework established, a number of modern novels concerned with history are then explored. Chapters devoted to Conrad's Nostromo, Ford's Parade's End, and Faulkner's Absolom, Absolom! examine the ultimate orthodox historiographical points of view in these novels, while a chapter on the fiction of African-American women engages the problem of historiography from the margins of the dominant culture. In the final chapter, Pynchon's V is the focus of a discussion of postmodernism and historical discourse. This is an original, interdisciplinary work which engages issues of contemporaray academic debate and illustrates its arguments with examples from well-known texts. The book is relevant to current debates in the problems of narrative representation both in fiction and the writing of history, while addressing questions being raised in literary studies concerning the representation of cultural difference and the varieties of social and discursive power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHistory in literature. 0aLiterature and history. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107804750 cprintz978074501283440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147446927240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474469272423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474469272/original  a978-3-11-078047-5  Edinburgh University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK